WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.640
Hey everyone, my name is Cecil and I'm here with my colleague Jay and we're part of the

00:00:11.640 --> 00:00:20.280
Posit support team and we're going to walk through today the creation of an SSL certificate.

00:00:20.280 --> 00:00:25.840
So in many cases there are a number of different commands you can use, but the one that we

00:00:25.840 --> 00:00:33.119
like to use for testing purposes is using OpenSSL. So this command, OpenSSL

00:00:33.119 --> 00:00:41.200
REC, creates the new certificate. Nodes, that's actually Nodes, which means the key

00:00:41.200 --> 00:00:46.959
file isn't password-protected. You will run into issues if the key file is

00:00:46.959 --> 00:00:54.639
password-protected. New creates a new certificate and X.509 is the file

00:00:54.639 --> 00:01:00.560
format. So in this case we're creating a key and a certificate file. So the key

00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:10.199
out flag dictates that the key is called PositKey with a .key extension and the

00:01:10.199 --> 00:01:16.360
dash out is for the certificate file. And in this case it's PositCert.crt.

00:01:16.360 --> 00:01:23.080
It's really important that the extension is either .crt or .pem. Otherwise

00:01:23.080 --> 00:01:27.639
you'll run into issues with Posit products. So when you create the

00:01:27.639 --> 00:01:33.199
certificate you'll get a hash that's generated for you and you'll need to

00:01:33.199 --> 00:01:38.000
fill in some details. So in this case you can put in your two-letter country code,

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:46.160
your state or province name, locality, organization name. A lot of these fields

00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:52.519
aren't crucial. The organizational unit name, this is just to identify the SSL

00:01:52.559 --> 00:01:58.639
certificate. The one that's really important is the common name, the CN of

00:01:58.639 --> 00:02:05.480
your SSL certificate. So this would need to match the FQDN or the DNS name of

00:02:05.480 --> 00:02:12.279
the server that you're installing the certificate on. And it's

00:02:12.279 --> 00:02:15.919
also important because if you were to generate this certificate and use it on

00:02:15.919 --> 00:02:22.000
another server you will run into issues because the FQDN will be different. So in

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:31.759
this case for testing purposes we can just have PositDemo.com and we

00:02:31.759 --> 00:02:39.360
need to make sure that the URL of our host is PositDemo.com. So email address,

00:02:39.360 --> 00:02:44.119
this is more just to identify the certificate, if it's globally routable so

00:02:44.119 --> 00:02:51.080
we can skip that. And yep, the certificate is generated.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:54.059
you

